    <title>Recipe: milk coffee</title>
    <updated>2026-01-25T22:53:50.583591+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>captainsblog</name>
      <email>hidden</email>
    </author>
    <content type="html">&lt;p&gt;For a while, I was on a quest for a perfect poor man’s latte, but now I’ve settled on something a little different: milk brewed coffee. After arriving at the technique, I searched online and couldn’t find anyone else making it the same way, so here’s my recipe.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Grind 1/3 cup of dark roast coffee on the finest grind setting.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Bring 1/3 cup of water to a boil.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Mix in the ground coffee and simmer until it thickens.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Pour in 14 ounces of milk and gradually heat until it reaches 190 degrees.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Strain the coffee through a metal coffee filter.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The resulting coffee is bold and agressive, it’s very hot and hits like a slap on the face to wake you up in the morning. I realize that not everyone likes coffee as intense as I do, and if that’s the case with you, any of the parameters can be adjusted for a milder brew.&lt;/p&gt;
</content>
    <link href="https://blog.thecaptain.dev/2026/january/coffee/" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-01-25T22:51:00+00:00</published>
